SCOS-2000 Database Standard

  • 1. Introduction

    SatView™ is designed to support a variety of telemetry data standards and database formats. This flexibility is achieved by separating all satellite dependencies from the core software and by taking advantage of sophisticated interfaces for the data exchange.

    Currently, the following telemetry data standards are supported:

    Project

    Telemetry Standard

    Database Format

    DBMS
    • ARTEMIS
    • Packet Telemetry (CCSDS 102.0-B-2)
    • ALTEL (Alenia+Telespazio)
    • Microsoft® SQL Server

  • 2. Architecture

    As mentioned before, SatView™ is designed to support a variety of database standards. This is realized by encapsulating the syntactical specifics into a separate executable module communicating with the invariant part of the software through a predefined interface. In cases where the database is built-up on different tables with other relationships, an additional software driver must be implemented by Binary Space containing information about the table design and parsing details. In the end, the complete database is always mapped into invariant internal data structures.
    The communication with the Database Management Systems (DBMS) is performed via the Open Database Connectivity (ODBC) standard.

  • 3. Supported Database Standards

    Up-to-now the database standards listed below are implemented:

    Standard

    Description
    • ALTEL
    • This database standard has been implemented to support the ARTEMIS satellite. It was issued by the ALTEL consortium.
    • SCOS-2000
    • This database standard has been implemented to support ESA projects. It can easily be adopted to specific missions.

    3.1.1. PMF Table

    This table defines the telemetry packets generated by the sub-systems and payload instruments.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    PMF_PACKID

    ch(4)

    Telemetry packet name

    Unique, not null

    2

    PMF_TYPE

    ch(1)

    Telemetry packet type

    Must be 0, not null

    3

    PMF_DESCR

    vc(32)

    Telemetry packet description

    None, not null

    4

    PMF_HFLG

    int

    Data field header flag:

    0=No header
    1=Header exists

    In set {0, 1}

    5

    PMF_APID

    ch(3)

    Application identifier (hex)

    In set {000, 001, 002, 003, 004, 011, 012, 013, 020, 021, 022}
    Not null

    6

    PMF_LENG

    int

    Packet data field size (in bytes) minus 1

    0-121
    Not null

    7

    PMF_TMTY

    ch(1)

    Telemetry type:

    0=Cyclic
    1=Exception
    2=Oversampled
    3=Report
    4=Dump

    In set {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} or null

    8

    PMF_TMID

    ch(2)

    Telemetry identifier (hex)

    00-FF or null

    9

    PMF_FUNC

    vc(254)

    Extended packet description

    None, null

    10

    PMF_SMPRT

    int

    Packet transmission rate (in seconds)

    ≥ 0 or null

    11

    PMF_VALID

    ch(6)

    Number of I/O failures before the packet is set to invalid (only used for AOCS oversampling)

    > 0 or null

    12

    PMF_VARIABLE

    int

    Variable packet length flag:

    0=Fixed length
    1=Variable length

    In set {0, 1) or null

    13

    PMF_3VAL

    vc(4)

    Third discriminator

    0000-FFFF or null

    14

    PMF_STATUS

    ch(1)

    Record change status:

    N=New
    T=Draft
    C=Changed
    D=Deleted

    In set {N, T, C, D} or null

    15

    PMF_DFH_NAME

    vc(12)

    Data field header name

    If PMF_HFLG = 1 then must be a valid data field header name
    If PMF_HFLG = 0 then must be null

    16

    PMF_VCID

    int

    Virtual channel identifier

    In set {0, 1}

    17

    PMF_EVENTID

    ch(6)

    Name of the event identifier parameter

    Must be a valid parameter name located in this packet or a DS16 parameter those parent is located there as well
    May be null

    Satview™ also supports the definition of alphanumeric displays via XML files.
    The following schema definition is used:

    <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
    <!ATTLIST ANDdef
    name CDATA #REQUIRED
    description CDATA #REQUIRED>
    <!ELEMENT ANDdef (ANDparamDef*, CommentLine*)>
    <!ELEMENT ANDparamDef EMPTY>
    <!ATTLIST ANDparamDef
    name CDATA #REQUIRED
    domain CDATA #OPTIONAL
    representation (SOURCE | CALIBRATED | DEFAULT) DEFAULT
    orderInDisplay CDATA #REQUIRED
    commutation CDATA 0
    format (BINARY | OCTAL | DECIMAL | HEXADECIMAL | NORMAL) NORMAL
    displayIfInvalid (true | false) false>
    <!ELEMENT CommentLine EMPTY>
    <!ATTLIST CommentLine
    orderInDisplay CDATA #REQUIRED
    comment CDATA #REQUIRED>

    Example:

    <?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
    <!DOCTYPE ANDdef SYSTEM 'ANDdef.dtd'>
    <ANDdef name="S2KAND01" description="32 Parameter Display"><ANDparamDef name="S2KTP301" orderInDisplay="0" commutation="0" format="BINARY" displayIfInvalid="true"/>
    <ANDparamDef name="S2KTP302" orderInDisplay="8" commutation="1" format="OCTAL" displayIfInvalid="true"/>
    <ANDparamDef name="S2KTP303" orderInDisplay="16” commutation="1" format="DECIMAL" displayIfInvalid="true"/>
    <ANDparamDef name="S2KTP304" orderInDisplay="24" commutation="1" format="HEXADECIMAL" displayIfInvalid="true"/>
    <ANDparamDef name="S2KTP305" orderInDisplay="31" commutation="1" format="NORMAL" displayIfInvalid="true"/>
    <CommentLine orderInDisplay="1" comment="This is 1st parameter"/>
    <CommentLine orderInDisplay="7" comment="This is 2nd parameter "/>
    <CommentLine orderInDisplay="25" comment="This is 3rd parameter "/>
    <CommentLine orderInDisplay="30" comment="This is 4th parameter "/>
    </ANDdef>

    The mapping between DBMS table and XML files is as follows:

    ANDDef Attribute

    DPF_TYPE

    -

    DPF_HEAD

    description

    Field Name

    ANDparamDef Attribute

    DPC_NUMBE

    -

    DPC_NAME

    name

    DPC_FLDN

    orderInDisplay

    DPC_COMM

    commutation

    DPC_MODE

    displayIfInvalid

    DPC_FORM

    format

    3.2.26. TCP Table

    This table defines all telecommand packet headers.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    TCP_ID

    vc(8)

    Name of the telecommand packet header

    Unique, not null

    2

    TCP_DESC

    vc(24)

    Textual description of the packet header

    None, null

    3.2.27. PCPC Table

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    PCPC_PNAME

    vc(8)

    Telecommand packet header parameter name

    Unique, not null

    2

    PCPC_DESC

    vc(24)

    Textual description of the header parameter

    None, null

    3

    PCPC_CODE

    3.2.28. PCDF Table

    This table defines the parameter locations for all fixed size telecommand packets.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    PCDF_TCNAME

    vc(8)

    Name of the telecommand packet header

    Valid packet header name
    Not null

    2

    PCDF_DESC

    vc(24)

    Textual description of this packet header element
    Note:
    This field is used for fixed areas only

    None, null

    3

    PCDF_TYPE

    ch(1)

    Type of the packet header element:

    F=Fixed area whose value is taken from PCDF_VALUE
    A=APID parameter whose value is to be taken from CCF_APID
    T=Service type parameter whose value is to be taken from CCF_TYPE
    S=Service sub-type parameter whose value is to be taken from CCF_STYPE
    K=Acknowledgement flags parameter whose value is to be taken from CCF_ACK
    P=Other packet parameter (value is automatically set)

    In set {F,A,T,S,K,P}
    Not null

    4

    PCDF_LEN

    num(4,0)

    Length of the packet header element (in bits)

    1-32
    Not null

    5

    PCDF_BIT

    num(4,0)

    Offset of the packet header element calculated from the start of the entire packet (in bits)

    0-9999
    Not null

    6

    PCDF_PNAME

    vc(8)

    Name of the packet header parameter
    Note:
    This field is only applicable if the packet header element is not of type fixed

    Valid parameter name or null

    7

    PCDF_VALUE

    vc(10)

    Value of the packet header element
    Note:
    The value must be expressed in either decimal or with the radix specified below (for unsigned integer format types)

    Valid number
    Not null

    8

    PCDF_RADIX

    ch(1)

    Packet header element value radix:

    D=Decimal
    O=Octal
    H=Hexadecimal

    Note:
    This field is only applicable if the parameter has an unsigned integer format type or if the packet header element is a fixed area

    In set {D,O,H}
    Not null

    3.2.29. CCF Table

    This table defines all telecommands.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    vc(64)

    Detailed description

    None, null

    4

    CCF_CTYPE

    vc(8)

    Telecommand type:

    R=Control Segment (a.k.a. Reset Map Command)
    F=Control Frame (a.k.a. BC frame i.e. Unlock and Set V(R))
    S=Command Packet which does not contain the Packet Error Control Field
    T=SLE Throw Event
    N=NIS Throw Event

    Note:
    For any other standard telecommand (i.e. except the special commands/directives listed above), this field can be left null or populated with any other character string (not matching R,F,S,T or N) with a mission specific meaning

    None, null

    5

    CCF_CRITICAL

    Y=Critical (hazardous)
    N=Non-critical

    In set {Y,N}
    Not null

    Not null

    0-255 or null if PCDF_TYPE=S (no entries)

    9

    CCF_APID

    Application identifier

    0-2047 for spacecraft telecommands

    Null if PCDF_TYPE=A (no entries)

    10

    N=Can only be loaded as part of a telecommand sequence

    In set {Y,N}
    Not null

    S=Interlocks local commanding for the sub-system that the command belongs to
    B=Interlocks global commanding only for the sub-system that the command belongs to
    N=No associated interlock

    In set {G,L,S,B,N}
    Not null

    U=Uplink (also referred to as radiation/ transmission)

    C=Completion

    3.2.32. CDF Table

    This table defines the application data field content for all telecommands.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    CDF_CNAME

    vc(8)

    Telecommand name

    Valid telecommand name
    Not null

    2

    CDF_ELTYPE

    ch(1)

    Telecommand element type:

    A=Fixed area
    F=Non-editable parameter
    E=Editable parameter

    In set {A,F,E}
    Not null

    3

    CDF_DESCR

    vc(24)

    Textual description of the element

    Null if CDF_ELTYPE<>A

    4

    CDF_ELLEN

    num(4,0)

    Element width (in bits)

    1-32 or 0 if CDF_ELTYPE<>A

    5

    CDF_BIT

    num(4,0)

    Element offset (in bits)
    Note:
    This field specifies the bit offset of this element relative to the start of the unexpanded telecom-mand application data field

    0-9999
    Not null

    6

    CDF_GRPSIZE

    num(2,0)

    Group size (in parameters)

    1-99 or 0

    7

    CDF_PNAME

    vc(8)

    Telecommand parameter

    Valid parameter name or null if CDF_ELTYPE=A

    8

    CDF_INTER

    ch(1)

    Default value interpretation flag:

    R=The value is raw (use CDF_VALUE)
    E=The value is expressed using an engineering representation (use CDF_VALUE)
    D=Use the value specified in CPC_DEFVAL
    T=Use the value provided by the telemetry parameter specified in CDF_TMID

    In set {R,E,D,T}
    Not null

    9

    CDF_VALUE

    vc(17)

    Default or fixed value
    Note:

    - If the element type is fixed, this value must be expressed with a hexadecimal radix
    - If it is a parameter, this value must be expressed as specified by CDF_INTER i.e. raw values must conform with CPC_PTC and CPC_RADIX and engineering values with CPC_DISPFMT
    - If this element is a parameter of type Command ID, this field (if not null) shall contain the name of a telecommanf not containing any parameter without default value
    - If this element is a parameter of type Parameter ID, this field (if not null) shall contain the name of a monitoring parameter which is associated to an on-board identifier
    - This field can take 32 bits value at maximum

    Valid value or null

    10

    CDF_TMID

    vc(8)

    Monitoring parameter used to extract dynamic default values

    Valid parameter name or null if CDF_INTER<>T

    3.2.34. CSS Table

    This table defines all telecommand sequence elements.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    CSS_SQNAME

    vc(8)

    Telecommand sequence name

    Valid sequence name
    Not null

    2

    CSS_COMM

    vc(32)

    Additional comment

    None, not null if CSS_TYPE=T

    3

    CSS_ENTRY

    num(5,0)

    Element entry number

    1-99999
    Not null

    4

    CSS_TYPE

    ch(1)

    Element type:

    C=Telecommand
    S=Telecommand sequence
    T=Textual comment
    F=Formal parameter representing a telecommand
    P=Formal parameter representing a telecommand sequence

    In set {C,S,T,F,P}
    Not null

    5

    CSS_ELEMID

    vc(8)

    Element identifier
    Note:

    - If the element is a telecommand, it must be a valid telecommand name not containing any parameter of type group repeater
    - If it is a telecommand sequence, it must be a valid sequence name
    - If it is a formal parameter, it must be a valid formal parameter name
    - For a textual comment it must be null

    Not null if CSS_TYPE<>T

    6

    CSS_NPARS

    num(3,0)

    Number of editable parameters this element has

    0-999 or null

    7

    CSS_MANDISP

    ch(1)

    Manual dispatch flag:

    Y=The telecommand associated with this element requires a separate manual dispatch
    N=No manual dispatch is required

    Note:
    This field must be left null if this element is a telecommand belonging to a group/block, unless this is the first one in the group/block

    In set {Y,N} or null

    8

    CSS_RELTYPE

    ch(1)

    Release delta time interpretation flag:

    R=This element’s release/start time has to be calculated relative to the release time of the previous telecommand in the expanded sequence (or relative to its own dispatch time in case this is a telecommand associated to a manual dispatch flag)
    A=The release/start time has to be calculated relative to the start time of the sequence that this element belongs to

    In set {R,A} or null

    9

    CSS_RELTIME

    vc(8)

    Delta release time
    Note:

    - If this element is a telecommand and CSS_RELTYPE=R & CSS_MANDISP=Y, then the absolute release time is calculated by adding this field to the dispatch time
    - If the same conditions as above apply but with the exception of CSS_MANDISP=N, then the absolute release time of this telecommand is calculated by adding this field to the release time of the last telecommand prior to this one in the expanded top level parent sequence
    - If this element is a telecommand and CSS_RELTYPE=A, then the absolute release time of this telecommand is calculated by adding this field to the release start time of the current sequence
    - If this element is a sequence and CSS_RELTYPE=R, then the release start time of this nested sequence is calculated by adding this field to the release time of the last telecommand in the expanded parent sequence prior to this nested sequence
    - If this element is a sequence and CSS_RELTYPE=A, then the release start time of this nested sequence is calculated by adding this field to the release start time of the current sequence
    - If this field is null and this element is a telecommand, it implies that it is not release time-tagged (ASAP release condition)
    If this field is null and this element is a sequence, it implies that this sequence has zero delta release start time
    - This field must be left null if this element is a telecommand belonging to a group/block, unless this is the first one in the group/block

    Valid delta time hh:mm:ss or null

    10

    CSS_EXTIME

    vc(17)

    Delta execution time
    Note:

    - If this element is a telecommand and CSS_PREVREL=R, then the absolute execution time is calculated by adding this field to the execution time of the last execution time-tagged telecommand prior to this one in the expanded top level parent sequence
    - If this element is a telecommand and CSS_PREVREL=A, then the absolute execution time is calculated by adding this field to the execution start time of the current sequence
    - If this element is a sequence and CSS_PREVREL=R, then the execution start time of this nested sequence is calculated by adding this field to the execution time of the last execution time-tagged telecommand prior to this one in the expanded top level parent sequence
    - If this element is a sequence and CSS_PREVREL=A, then the execution start time of this nested sequence is calculated by adding this field to the execution start time of the current sequence
    - If this field is null and this element is a telecommand, it implies that it is not execution time-tagged
    If this field is null and this element is a sequence, it implies that this sequence has zero delta execution start time

    Valid delta time [-]d.hhh:mm:ss or null

    11

    CSS_PREVREL

    ch(1)

    Execution delta time interpretation flag:

    R=This element’s execution/start time has to be calculated relative to the execution time-tag of the previous time-tagged telecommand in the expanded sequence
    A=The execution/start time has to be calculated relative to the start time of the sequence that this element belongs to

    In set {R,A} or null

    12

    CSS_GROUP

    ch(1)

    Grouping condition flag:

    S=Start of the group
    M=Middle of a group
    E=End of a group

    Note:

    - This field is only applicable for telecommands
    - Only the first telecommand in the group is allowed to be associated to the manual dispatch flag and/or to a release time-tag

    In set {S,M,E} or null

    13

    CSS_BLOCK

    ch(1)

    Blocking condition flag:

    S=Start of the block
    M=Middle of a block
    E=End of a block

    Note:

    - This field is only applicable for telecommands
    - Only the first telecommand in the block is allowed to be associated to the manual dispatch flag and/or to a release time-tag
    - It is not allowed to include high-priority commands in a block

    In set {S,M,E} or null

    14

    CSS_ILSCOPE

    ch(1)

    Interlock flag:

    G=The telecommand will globally interlock the whole system
    L=Interlocks only the local commanding source
    S=Interlocks local commanding for the sub-system that the telecommand belongs to
    B=Interlocks global commanding only for the sub-system that the telecommand belongs to
    F=Interlocks only the local commanding source and only in case of verification failure (i.e. no WAIT state)
    T=Interlocks local commanding for the sub-system that the telecommand belongs to and only in case of verification failure (i.e. no WAIT state)
    N=No associated interlock

    Note:

    - This field is only applicable for telecommands
    - In the case of telecommands belonging to a block/group, options G and L are only allowed for the last telecommand in the block/group

    In set {G,L,S,B,F,T,N} or null

    15

    CSS_ILSTAGE

    ch(1)

    Interlock verification stage type:

    R=Reception/acceptance at the ground station
    U=Uplink (also referred to as radiation/ transmission)
    O=On-board reception/acceptance (final uplink verification)
    A=On-board application acceptance
    C=Completion

    Note:
    This field only applicable for telecommands

    In set {R,U,O,A,C} or null

    16

    CSS_DYNPTV

    ch(1)

    Dynamic pre-transmission validation check flag:

    Y=Override the related telecommand flag
    N=Use the telecommand’s flag

    Note:
    This field only applicable for telecommands

    In set {Y,N} or null

    17

    CSS_STAPTV

    ch(1)

    Pre-transmission validation check flag:

    Y=Override the related telecommand flag
    N=Use the telecommand’s flag

    Note:
    This field only applicable for telecommands

    In set {Y,N} or null

    18

    CSS_CEV

    ch(1)

    Telecommand execution verification flag:

    Y=Override the related telecommand flag
    N=Use the telecommand’s flag

    Note:
    This field only applicable for telecommands

    In set {Y,N} or null

    3.2.35. SDF Table

    This table defines all telecommand sequence element parameters.

    No.

    Column

    Type

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    SDF_SQNAME

    vc(8)

    Telecommand sequence name

    Valid sequence name
    Not null

    2

    SDF_ENTRY

    num(5,0)

    Element entry number

    1-99999
    Not null

    3

    SDF_ELEMID

    vc(8)

    Element name

    Valid telecommand, sequence or formal parameter name
    Not null

    4

    SDF_POS

    num(4,0)

    Element position
    Note:

    - If the sequence element is a telecommand, then this field specifies the bit offset of the parameter in the com¬mand
    If telecommands containing group repeaters are used, the value of this field shall be the bit offset expected for the current parameter following expansion of the groups
    - If it is a nested sequence, then this field specifies the sequence parameter position

    0-9999
    Not null

    5

    SDF_PNAME

    vc(8)

    Element parameter name

    Valid (formal) parameter name
    Not null

    6

    SDF_FTYPE

    ch(1)

    Element value modification flag:

    F=Non-modifiable value
    E=Editable value

    In set {F,E}
    Not null

    7

    SDF_VTYPE

    ch(1)

    Element value source flag:

    R=Use the raw value specified in SDF_VALUE
    E=Use the calibrated value specified in SDF_VALUE
    F=Use the value attached to the formal parameter specified in SDF_VALUE
    P=Use the value specified by the parameter value set in SDF_VALSET
    S=Use the value in CSP_DEFVAL attached to the formal parameter specified by this element
    D=Use the value specified at the corresponding position of the telecommand (CDF_VALUE)

    In set {R,E,F,P,S,D}
    Not null

    8

    SDF_VALUE

    vc(17)

    Element value
    Note:

    - If SDF_VTYPE is R or E, this value must be expressed using the appropriate representation i.e. raw values must be expressed in a format compatible with the type of the parameter, engineering values must be expressed in a format compatible with the engineering representation of the parameter
    - If SDF_VTYPE is R and this element parameter is of type Command ID, this field shall contain the name of a telecommand not containing any parameter without default value; if this element parameter is of type Parameter ID, this field shall contain the name of a monitoring parameter which is associated to an on-board identifier
    - If SDF_VTYPE is F, this field contains the name of the formal parameter which this element parameter will inherit the value from

    Valid value or null if SDF_VTYPE in set {D,P,S}

    9

    SDF_VALSET

    vc(8)

    Parameter value set value name

    Valid parameter set name or null if SDF_VTYPE<>P

    10

    Telecommand parameter repeated position
    Note:
    This field specifies the original bit offset of the parameter in the telecommand definition

    0-9999 or null

    The following table describes the structure of the memory model import/export file header:

    Line

    Name

    Size

    Description

    Restrictions

    1

    Description

    64

    Free textual description of the memory model used for display purposes

    None, not null

    2

    Category

    1

    Memory model category flag:

    C=Configuration tables i.e. memory models which can be used for the generation of patch/dump command data and thus are supposed to contain non-overlapping (but not necessarily contiguous) memory area definitions
    S=Symbolic tables i.e. memory models which cannot be used for the generation of command data. Typically, symbolic tables are used to provide a detailed interpretation of a memory image. They are allowed to contain ‘nested’ memory area definitions (i.e. areas which overlap but such that one area is completely contained in another one)

    In set {C,S}
    Not null

    Memory Device

    8

    Memory device name

    None, null

    Memory address base:

    1=Bytes
    2=Words
    4=Double-words

    5

    1

    Patch category flag:

    P=Patchable i.e. the area has to be used for off-line comparison and patched only if changed
    N=Not patchable
    M=Mandatory i.e. the area has to be patched anyhow (even if not changed)

    In set {P,N,M}
    Not null

    6

    Dump

    1

    Dump/monitor category flag:

    D=Dumpable only i.e. the area shall be dumped, used for off-line comparison but not used for monitoring
    N=Not dumpable
    M=Mandatory i.e. the area shall be dumped and shall be used for both monitoring and off-line comparison

    In set {D,N,M}
    Not null

    64

    Textual comment

    None, null

    Notes:

    -Use a separate file for each memory model definition
    -Specify one line for each memory area definition
    -Use CR for line separators, TABs for column delimiters

    Memory images definition import/export files have the following structure:

    DEVICE=Memory Device Name
    VERSION=Version/Issue
    UNIT=Address Base
    START=Start Address (hex),COUNT=Length (hex),DATA=Data (hex)
    {START=Start Address (hex),COUNT=Length (hex),DATA=Data (hex)}

    Notes:

    -Use a separate file for each memory image definition
    -Use CR for line separators
